Claims WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. A medical device system comprising: a therapy delivery circuit configured to deliver an electrical stimulation therapy; a sensing circuit configured to receive one or more electrophysiological signals via a medical electrical lead having a distal end and carrying at least a distal electrode, the one or more electrophysiological signals including a distal vector signal received via a distal sensing electrode vector that includes the distal electrode; a control circuit in communication with the sensing circuit and the therapy delivery circuit, the control circuit configured to: based on the one or more electrophysiological signals received by the sensing circuit, control the therapy delivery circuit to deliver the electrical stimulation therapy; based on at least the distal vector signal, detect migration of the medical electrical lead carrying the distal electrode; and generate an output in response to detecting the migration of the medical electrical lead; and a memory configured to store data corresponding to the generated output. 2. The medical device system of claim 1 wherein the control circuit is further configured to: determine a first feature of the distal vector signal at a first timepoint; determine a second feature of the distal vector signal at a second timepoint; and detect migration of the medical electrical lead based on at least a difference between the first feature and the second feature. 3. The medical device system of claim 2 wherein the control circuit is further configured to determine the first feature and the second feature by determining at least one of: a peak amplitude; a peak polarity; a waveform morphology template; a slope; 

 a signal width; or a signal area. 4. The medical device system of any one of claims 2 â 3 wherein: the sensing circuit is further configured to receive a proximal vector signal via a proximal sensing electrode vector including a proximal electrode carried by the medical electrical lead, the proximal electrode spaced proximally from the distal electrode on the medical electrical lead, the proximal sensing electrode vector not including the distal electrode; and the control circuit is further configured to: determine a difference between the distal vector signal and the proximal vector signal; and detect migration of the medical electrical lead based on at least the difference between the distal vector signal and the proximal vector signal and a difference between the first feature and the second feature of the distal vector signal. 5. The medical device system of any one of claims 2 â 4 wherein: the sensing circuit is further configured to receive a proximal vector signal via a proximal sensing electrode vector including a proximal electrode carried by the medical electrical lead, the proximal electrode spaced proximally from the distal electrode on the medical electrical lead, the proximal sensing electrode vector not including the distal electrode; and the control circuit is further configured to: determine a third feature of the proximal vector signal at the first timepoint; determine a fourth feature of the proximal vector signal at the second timepoint; and detect migration of the medical electrical lead based on at least the difference between the first feature and the second feature meeting a first threshold and a difference between the third feature and the fourth feature meeting a second threshold. 6. The medical device system of claim 5 wherein the control circuit is further configured to determine that the difference between the third feature and the fourth feature meet the second threshold when the difference between the third feature and the fourth feature is less than the second threshold. 7. The medical device system of any one of claims 1 â 6 wherein: the sensing circuit is further configured to receive a proximal vector signal via a proximal sensing electrode vector including a proximal electrode carried by the medical electrical lead, the proximal electrode spaced proximally from the distal electrode on the medical electrical lead, the proximal sensing electrode vector not including the distal electrode; and the control circuit is further configured to detect the migration of the medical electrical lead based on at least the distal vector signal by: determining a combined signal from the distal vector signal and the proximal vector signal at a first timepoint; determining the combined signal from the distal vector signal and the proximal vector signal at a second timepoint; detecting a change in the combined signal determined at the second timepoint relative to the combined signal determined at the first timepoint; and detecting migration of the medical electrical lead carrying the distal electrode based on the detected change in the combined signal. 8. The medical device system of any one of claims 1 â 7 wherein the control circuit is configured to generate the output by generating a lead migration detection notification; and the medical device system further comprises a telemetry circuit configured to transmit the lead migration detection notification. 9. The medical device system of any one of claims 1 â 8 wherein the control circuit is further configured to generate the output by at least one of: adjusting a sensing control parameter in response to detecting the migration of the medical electrical lead; 

 adjusting an arrhythmia detection control parameter in response to detecting the migration of the medical electrical lead; performing a capture test in response to detecting the migration of the medical electrical lead; or adjusting a therapy control parameter used by the therapy delivery circuit to deliver the electrical stimulation therapy. 10. The medical device system of any one of claims 1 â 9 wherein the control circuit is further configured to generate the output by disabling the electrical stimulation therapy in response to detecting the migration of the medical electrical lead. 11. The medical device system of any one of claims 1 â 10 wherein: the sensing circuit is further configured to: sense the one or more electrophysiological signals by sensing an atrial signal and a ventricular signal; sense P-waves from the atrial signal; and sense R-waves from the ventricular signal; and the control circuit is further configured to: detect one of suspected cardiac event signal oversensing or suspected cardiac event signal undersensing by the sensing circuit based on at least one of the sensed atrial signal, the sensed P-waves, the sensed ventricular signal or the sensed R-waves; and responsive to detecting one of the suspected cardiac event signal oversensing or the suspected cardiac event signal undersensing, perform a lead migration check for detecting the migration of the medical electrical lead based on at least the distal vector signal. 12. The medical device system of any one of claims 1 â 11 wherein: the therapy delivery circuit is configured to deliver the electrical stimulation therapy by delivering a high voltage cardioversion/defibrillation shock; and 

 the control circuit is further configured to perform a lead migration check for detecting the migration of the medical electrical lead in response to the therapy delivery circuit delivering the high voltage cardioversion/defibrillation shock. 13. The medical device system of any one of claims 1 â 12 wherein the control circuit is further configured to: determine at a first time point, from the distal vector signal, a first quantitative relationship between a distal vector signal first positive peak amplitude and a distal vector signal first negative peak amplitude; determine at a second time point later than the first time point, from the distal vector signal, a second quantitative relationship between a distal vector signal second positive peak amplitude and a distal vector signal second negative peak amplitude; and detect the migration of the medical electrical lead based on at least the distal vector signal by detecting the migration of the medical electrical lead based on at least the first quantitative relationship and the second quantitative relationship. 14. The medical device system of any one of claims 1 â 13 further comprising the medical electrical lead, wherein the medical electrical lead is an extra-cardiac lead, wherein the control circuit being further configured to detect migration of the medical electrical lead after implantation of the medical electrical lead in an extra-cardiac location. 15. The medical device system of any one of claims 1-14 wherein: the therapy delivery circuit is further configured to deliver the electrical stimulation therapy by delivering a cardiac electrical stimulation therapy; and the sensing circuit is further configured to receive the one or more electrophysiological signals by sensing at least one cardiac electrical signal.
